[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing test coverage issues**\n\nIt seems the build report was likely generated before our test, but the user mentioned that there was no coverage after the last report. I need to identify coverage logs for test executions to see if the BCGOST test didn’t compile due to being untracked at the time of the report. Hmm, it could be that without a public API needing tests, there was no direct reflection. I also wonder if the workflow missed untracked files, but it will catch those in the final analysis.\n\n**Examining test coverage and serialization**\n\nI’m figuring out how active call sites are identified during the native image compile through static analysis, and how coverage is determined based on the JVM agent. The test needs to cover these call sites effectively. If the serialization methods like private writeObject/readObject aren't instrumented, it could explain the stale report despite similar tests showing zero. Perhaps the issue comes from how classes are named or if there are filters applied to user code. The inner class ExposedKeyFactorySpi might be excluded from instrumentation, affecting coverage.\n\n**Investigating test execution and report issues**\n\nI’m considering whether the native image reachability might be excluding crucial elements that could lead to compile failures. The agent’s user-code filter only allows specific packages, which means that if an inner class isn't included, reflection on it won't be recorded, but that shouldn't stop the test execution itself. I wonder if the issue lies in how the reports might be coming from a previous run, especially with an uncommitted new test not being tracked by git. I should check the JUnit patterns in build.gradle for clarity!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0769aab4046aa7850169fbea684d68819e98430d621767ae75\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp--pzTjJ1-R9kOU0yqpEqsR